This was not intentional, but I think that posting my video on the Day of Silence is very fitting. The project goes live in just 10 minutes and I hope you can join me for the premiere 💕 In recent times, there has been a growing fear-mongering campaign that claims LGBT+ individuals are trying to indoctrinate children into being gay or trans. This hour long video investigates whether or not there is any truth to these claims (spoiler: there is not.) Additionally, it discusses how mainstream media which pushed this narrative and specifically targeted my videos/book affected me psychologically. Given the current political climate, it is more important than ever to dispel these harmful myths and misconceptions. The attack on trans youth is a real and pressing issue that demands our attention and support. I hope this video helps to educate and inform those who have been misled by these harmful sentiments 🏳️‍⚧️💙 (music by trans artist @reneeyoxon)

In my newest video essay I challenge the explosive wave of claims we’ve seen around the world recently which contend that LGBT+ folks are trying to indoctrinate children. I poured quite a bit of my heart into it, and to spread the love I’ll be liking and following a bunch of cool folks who share this on their story, insta feed, twitter, YouTube, whatever! 💕 Link is in my bio for those who want to watch 💙🏳️‍⚧️

A few weeks ago I did my first big postpartum fitness thing! My friend and I ran 10 miles in Goldy’s run. We were not fast by any means, but we had a ton of fun, aaaaand we trained enough to NOT be sore/injured the following day, which I was pretty proud of 😎 …It’s hard to describe how different re-conditioning my body feels after having 2 kids. I was pretty sick and sedentary for a lot of my pregnancy, so there were tons of ups and downs getting back fitness. If you wanna hear more about that, I just posted a video on my 2nd channel (link in bio.) Otherwise, wish me and Brianna luck on our first half marathon that we are signed up for May 27th 😬🏃‍♂️

Happy mother/parent’s day! Lots of folks ask if Gray and I go by “mom,” “dad,” or something else, and the answer is - we are comfy with all respectful labels that signify parent. Throughout the week we both usually switch between words and phrases like, “mom,” “mama A,” “mama G,” “dad,” “other dad,” “stinky dad,” “dadarino,” “parent,” etc. We are happy with our kids and others using any of these qualifiers for us. We discussed it, and the only situation that would make us uncomfortable, would be if someone strictly assigned one of us “mom” and the other one “dad,” since that feels like it’s trying to stick us in a very rigid cis/het box that just isn’t us 🤷🏼‍♂️ So as long as you’re not doing that, and staying respectful, call us anything you like! If YOU are a queer parent, I’d love to hear what words you use to describe the folks in your family ☺️ …Also, my children (and some helpers) made these cute gifts with their little feetsies 😍 What talented sweeties!!

Introducing a new segment (tentatively) called #30FlirtyAndLearningToCook 😋 My entire life, cooking was never really a skill developed, but as I get older I can feel such a huge difference when I fill my body with tasty, fresh(ish), and nutrient dense foods. I love that I know exactly what I’m eating when I make my own food, and I feel proud of myself for creating something. Plus, I save soooo much money - ordering is like a gazillion dollars these days! The only problem with cooking is…I don’t know what I’m doing, and I’m a pro at quitting half way through bc ADHD. Seriously, before this year, cereal and easy mac were kind of my culinary peaks. So, with these posts I hope to share some suuuper easy recipes (honestly some I’d barely consider cooking) that might encourage was other cooking-late-bloomers to give it a shot! Other things about this series are, I hate measuring (so many dishes and numbers to keep track of when you measure, yuck) so none of my dishes involve precise measurements, and the steps are minimal bc I get bored fast 😋 …Also, a bunch of these meals can be made in batches so you can eat it throughout the week or freeze it for later! 

Alright, this is chickpea curry! All I did was…
1) Prepare some rice. 
2) Sauté some onions and minced garlic in olive oil (until onions are translucent-ish and garlic starts to brown.)
3) Add a can of rinsed chickpeas and a packet of pre-made curry to the pan and simmer (I get a lot of my curry packets at Trader Joe’s, and while this obvs won’t taste as good good making your own fresh curry sauce, it’s still pretty good I think 😊) 
4) And if you wanna be fancy, top with fresh parsley and toasted cashews!

On scales of 1-10 for taste, price, and ease of cooking (10’s being delicious, cheap, and easy) I would gives this…

Taste: 8 (yummy, filling, warm, kind of simple)
Price: 10 (less than $3 for meal, less than $10-15 for all ingredients, most which have a long shelf life)
Ease: 8 (sautéing the onions and garlic is the most advanced part)

There ya go! I know it’s simple, but it’s full of fiber, protein, and leaves you with 2-3 dishes to wash after!

Installment 2 of #30FlirtyAndLearningToCook 👨‍🍳 …I have discovered that I really like bowls because they are more assembly than cooking haha. This salmon grain bowl is carb and protien heavy which has been super helpful for my fitness journey. To make this, I…

1) Prepared some quinoa (basically bring some quinoa + 1.5x as much water to a boil, then simmer for 15min)
2) Soft boiled an egg (I have an egg cooker, which makes cooking eggs so easy, bc I just add water and press a button)
3) Placed eggs and quinoa in a bowl and added some smoked salmon and a dollop of plain Greek yogurt
4) Topped with parsley, dill, salt, and pepper 

On scales of 1-10 for taste, price, and ease of cooking (10 being delicious, cheap, and easy) I give this…

Taste: 7.5 (filling, salty, usually ate cold though which isn’t always as satisfying)
Price: 6 (packages of smoked salmon and eggs are kinda pricy. $5 for meal, $15 for all ingredients)
Ease: 9 (and if you prepare a big batch of quinoa and a few eggs, you are good to go for several meals and minimal effort!)

If you have an easy recipe you want me to try, comment below!

It’s another #30FlirtyAndLearningToCook! This pesto and egg toast is an easy breakfast and will make you feel fancy! All I did was…

1) Toast some bread (I am obsessed with ‘Super Bread’ from Trader Joe’s - not spon. It’s nutty, full of grains, and has so much fiber and protein!) 
2) Spread some mascarpone (you could substitute ricotta or just skip the cheese entirely if you want tho) and pesto spread on top.
3) Then I poached an egg, and I promised it’s easier than you think!! Basically, you just drop an egg in boiling water with like 2 extra steps. While I could explain it from start to finish, if you search “how to poach an egg” on TikTok you will get a ton of 30 second, simple tutorials - I like the one by “Half Batch Baking.” But I swear, it is not hard and only takes about 2-3 min! 
3) Top with salt, pepper, and red chili flakes 🌶️

On scales of 1-10 for taste, price, and ease of cooking (10 being delicious, cheap, and easy) I give this…

Taste: 9.5 (My new fav breakfast)
Price: 6 (Eggs are kinda expensive and mascarpone is too. You can make this cheaper tho by using ricotta or cutting the cheese entirely. As is, this is about $5 for meal, $11-14 for all ingredients)
Ease: 7 (Only bc poaching the egg is intimidating the first time…after you get over that, it’s an 8)

And this only has 4 dishes (strainer, pot, plate, and knife!) What do you like to put on toast to feel shmancy? 🙂

Installment 4 of #30FlirtyAndLearningToCook. I am back with another bowl. This one, however, is just a tad more involved. To make this I…

1) Pickled some red onion beforehand (To do this thinly slice red onion and put it in mason jar. Then bring 1 part vinegar and 1 part water to just under a boil. Add this to the jar and transfer to the fridge once cool.)
2) Prepared some saffron rice (basically steep some saffron threads in warm water and add that mixture to some cooked rice with a little butter and salt.)
3) Cooked some beef kebab from Trader Joe’s (This is so easy and you can cook them from frozen. Just pop the kebabs into an oven at 350 for 25 min. Done.)
4) Topped the rice with rinsed chickpeas, pita bread from Trader Joe’s, tzatziki sauce from Trader Joe’s, feta, sliced avocado, tomato, pickled onion, and the kebab. 

On scales of 1-10 for taste, price, and ease of cooking (10 being delicious, cheap, and easy) I give this…

Taste: 9.5 (This was my fav so far! So full of variety and tons of really yummy Mediterranean flavors.)
Price: 7 (I got everything at TJ’s which I feel like is mostly pretty cheap. The only downfall is this dish requires a lot of ingredients. $3.80 for meal, $19 for all ingredients.)
Ease: 5.5 (The rice and pickled onions are the hardest part about the dish. If you skipped the onions though the ease becomes a 7.)

As always, if you have an easy recipes you want me to try, comment below!

Woo! Another #30FlirtyAndLearningToCook this one is super simple and fitness inspired 💪💪💪 For these high protein pancakes all you need to do is…

1. Gather your 4 ingredients: 1/3 cup egg whites, 1/4 cup Greek yogurt, 1/2 teaspoon baking powder, and enough protein powder to get it to a normal pancake batter consistency. For the powder I use, it takes 1 1/2 scoops. 
2) Mix everything together.
3) Cook on the stove! 

With the yogurt (Oikos) and protein powder (Gold Standard Vanilla) that I use, it’s almost 40g of protein!

On scales of 1-10 for taste, price, and ease of cooking (10 being delicious, cheap, and easy) I give this…

Taste: 6.5 (Not as good as traditional pancakes, but still warm, sweet, and yummy!)
Price: 9 (These were all ingredients that I usually have in my house so it felt free for me! But even when I buy this stuff, nothing is very expensive.)
Ease: 9 (This is so simple and only takes 5 min. It does involve some measuring, which I usually dislike, but it’s minimal and feels worth it.)

Throw back to this refreshing #30FlirtyAndLearningToCook dish that I used to make in the summer. It’s one of my favs! To make these spicy, peanuty cucumber “noodles” I…

1) Make cucumber ribbons by simply using a vegetable peeler. 
2) Create the sauce by mixing spicy chili crisp, peanut butter, and soy sauce. 
3) Combine the cucumbers and sauce.
4) Top with sesame seeds to be fun!

On scales of 1-10 for taste, price, and ease of cooking (10 being delicious, cheap, and easy) I give this…

Taste: 9.5 (So good!)
Price: 9 (One you have all the spices and sauces in your arsenal, the only real cost is a cucumber.)
Ease: 8.5 (I think this dish has the highest overall score out of anything I’ve posted so far!)
